<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="389" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Adult male.</emphasis>
Coloration of the body in alcohol stramineous. Length of forewings 5.4 mm (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">n</emphasis>
= 18). We were not able to observe the coloration of the wings in the specimens preserved in alcohol due to discoloration of the cuticle through time, but Flint (1983) described it from dried specimens as follows: &quot;forewings dark purplish black in basal quarter and in two transverse bands apicad, otherwise covered with golden hair&quot;.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Head</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Heads in dorsal view of the species of the Smicridea brasiliana group A Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) brasiliana B S. (R.) weidneri C S. (R.) vermiculata D S. (R.) atrobasis E S. (R.) nanda. Abbreviations: CSL length of the coronal suture, IOD interocular distance, MEW maximum eye width, MHW maximum head width. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712814" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">1D</figureCitation>
). In dorsal view rectangular, transverse. Mesal margins of the eyes, in dorsal view, convex, postgenal areas reduced. Interocular area rectangular, narrow, longer than wide. Interocular distance 7.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
shorter than MHW. Coronal suture 2.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than IOD. Eyes very prominent, maximum eye width 2.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
shorter than MHW. Anterolateral setose warts present, elongate, oval. Posterior setose warts subtriangular. Maxillary palp formula: I, II-III, IV-V.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Male genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Anterolateral margin of segment IX sinuous. Tergum of segment X triangular in lateral view, dorsal and ventral margins rounded, with a ventral sclerotized Y-shaped area directed anteriorly through segment IX (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6A</figureCitation>
); in dorsal view divided mesally into two triangular hemitergites, with apex pointed, mesal margins concave (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6B</figureCitation>
). Inferior appendages with two articules, basal article slightly widened distally, apical one curved mesad in dorsal view, apex pointed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6A, B</figureCitation>
). Phallus long, with a tubular phallobase; basal portion broad, forming an angle of ~ 120° with distal part; apex broadened, ending in two laterodorsal and two lateroventral lobes, that become directed basad as the endotheca is everted (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6A, C, D</figureCitation>
). Internal sclerotized section of ejaculatory duct ~ 2/3 the phallobase length, straight, slightly upturned apically in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6A, C</figureCitation>
); in dorsal view longitudinally divided in two, apex shaped like an arrowhead (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">6D</figureCitation>
). Endotheca simple.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712819" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" start="Figure 6" startId="F6">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Figure 6.</emphasis>
Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrobasis" subGenus="Rhyacophylax">Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) atrobasis</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">A</emphasis>
segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">B</emphasis>
segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">C</emphasis>
tip of the phallus, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">D</emphasis>
tip of the phallus, dorsal view (left evaginated, right invaginated).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="389" type="systematic considerations">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Systematic considerations.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
This species seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1918" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Smicridea mesembrina" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesembrina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Smicridea mesembrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These two species bear apicolateral lobes on the phallus, but while the apex of the sclerotized section of the ejaculatory duct in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. mesembrina" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesembrina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. mesembrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is simple, in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. atrobasis" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrobasis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. atrobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is shaped like an arrowhead. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. atrobasis" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrobasis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. atrobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very distinctive feature that is the prominent eyes and reduced interocular area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
